value.value: An autosomal recessive condition caused by mutation(s) in the GTPBP3 gene, encoding tRNA modification GTPase GTPBP3, mitochondrial. It is characterized by childhood onset of hypertrophic cardiomyopathy and/or neurologic symptoms.

label.value: Plasma Cell to Total Cell Ratio Measurement

value.value: The determination of the ratio of the total plasma cells to total cells present in a sample. The measurement may be expressed as a ratio or percentage.

An autosomal dominant condition caused by mutation(s) caused by mutation(s) in the PIK3CD gene, encoding phosphatidylinositol 4,5-bisphosphate 3-kinase catalytic subunit delta isoform. It is characterized by defects in T-cells and B-cells and recurrent sinopulmonary infections in childhood.
An X-linked condition caused by mutation(s) in the BGN gene, encoding biglycan. It is characterized by cardiovascular defects and abnormal facies.
A type of centrifugation used to separate cell components.  Consists of two basic procedures: differential centrifugation and density gradient centrifugation.
A multichannel imaging method that uses light wave interference to generate information about targets in the micron range.

label.value: Thyroid Gland Mixed Medullary and Follicular Carcinoma

value.value: A primary carcinoma of the thyroid gland containing a medullary carcinoma component that is immunohistochemically positive for calcitonin, and follicular carcinoma component that is immunohistochemically positive for thyroglobulin.

label.value: Thyroid Gland Mixed Medullary and Papillary Carcinoma

value.value: A primary carcinoma of the thyroid gland containing a medullary carcinoma component that is immunohistochemically positive for calcitonin, and papillary carcinoma component that is immunohistochemically positive for thyroglobulin.

An invasive adenocarcinoma of the thyroid gland characterized by the presence of cells that secrete eosinophilic material. It is composed of cystic spaces, tubular structures, and solid areas. ETV6 translocations and ETV6-NTRK3 fusion are present.

A high-grade, rapidly growing malignant embryonal neoplasm that arises from the thyroid gland. It is characterized by the presence of primitive follicular-like structures surrounded by primitive small cells and primitive spindle cell mesenchymal stroma. It is associated with DICER1 gene mutations. The prognosis is poor.
The portion of the cingulate gyrus that lies inferior to the superior frontal gyrus, and is separated from it by the cingulate sulcus; it ends inferior to the rostrum of the corpus callosum.

A fusion gene that results from a chromosomal translocation t(11;14)(q13;q32) which places the CCND1 gene within a promoter region located in the immunoglobulin heavy chain gene locus (IGH). This rearrangement is associated with numerous lymphoproliferative B-cell malignancies.
A dosing unit for the number of therapeutic cells administered, expressed as 10 to the ninth power.
The mucosal membranes that line the nasal cavity.

The hydrochloride salt of an orally bio-available quinazoline with potential antineoplastic and radiosensitizing activities. Canertinib binds to the intracellular domains of epidermal growth factor receptor tyrosine kinases (ErbB family), irreversibly inhibiting their signal transduction functions and resulting in tumor cell apoptosis and suppression of tumor cell proliferation. This agent also acts as a radiosensitizing agent and displays synergistic activity with other chemotherapeutic agents.
Methods of fractionation, isolation, and purification based on the physico-chemical properties of the substance, e.g. crystallization, distillation, solubility (miscibility).
A question about how often an individual has or had a drink containing alcohol.

label.value: How Many Alcoholic Drinks Had on Typical Day When Drinking

value.value: A question about how many drinks containing alcohol an individual has or had on a typical day when they are drinking.

label.value: How Often Have Five or More Drinks on One Occasion

value.value: A question about how often an individual has or had five or more alcoholic drinks on one occasion.

label.value: How Often Have Four or More Drinks on One Occasion

value.value: A question about how often an individual has or had four or more alcoholic drinks on one occasion.

label.value: How Often During Last Year Have You Been Unable to Stop Drinking Once Started

value.value: A question about how often during the last year an individual found that they were not able to stop drinking once they had started.

label.value: How Often During Last Year Failed to do what was Normally Expected Because of Drinking

value.value: A question about how often during the last year an individual has or had failed to do what was normally expected of them because of drinking.

label.value: How Often During Last Year Needed First Drink in Morning to get Going After Heavy Drinking Session

value.value: A question about how often during the last year an individual needs or needed a first drink in the morning to get themselves going after a heavy drinking session.

label.value: How Often During Last Year Felt Guilt or Remorse After Drinking

value.value: A question about how often during the last year an individual has or had a feeling of guilt or remorse after drinking.

label.value: How Often During Last Year Been Unable to Remember What Happened the Night Before Because of Drinking

value.value: A question about how often during the last year an individual has or had been unable to remember what happened the night before because of their drinking.

label.value: Have You or Someone Else Been Injured Because of Your Drinking

value.value: A question about whether an individual or someone else has been injured because of the individual's drinking.

label.value: Frederick Cancer Research and Development Center

value.value: A government-owned, contractor operated cancer research facility located in Frederick, MD.  Operated under the direction of the Division of Cancer Biology.

label.value: Has Relative, Friend, Doctor, or Other Health Care Worker Been Concerned About Your Drinking or Suggested You Cut Down

value.value: A question about whether an individual's relative, friend, doctor, or other health care worker has been concerned about the individual's drinking or suggested they cut down.

label.value: Yes, but Not in Last Year

value.value: A response indicating that something has occurred, but not in the last year.
A response indicating that something has occurred during the last year.

A teratoma that arises outside an endocrine organ and shows endocrine differentiation. The endocrine component ranges from benign endocrine tissue to malignant endocrine neoplasms. This category includes struma ovarii, thyroid carcinoma arising in struma ovarii, and carcinoid tumor arising in ovarian teratoma.
A finding in a tissue sample indicating the presence of epithelial cells that synthesize and secrete hormones.
An ovarian teratoma characterized by the presence of a neoplastic neuroendocrine component consistent with carcinoid tumor.

A fusion gene that results from a chromosomal translocation, t(4;14)(p16;q32), which results in promoter exchange between the immunoglobulin heavy chain (IGH) gene locus and the FGFR3 gene. This rearrangement is associated with multiple myeloma.

A fusion gene that results from a chromosomal translocation, t(6;14)(p21.1;q32.3), which fuses transcriptional enhancers of the immunoglobulin heavy chain (IGH) gene locus with the 5' regulatory region of the CCND3 gene. This rearrangement is associated with multiple myeloma, diffuse large B-cell lymphoma (DLBCL) and marginal zone lymphoma.

A fusion gene that results from a chromosomal translocation, t(14;16)(q32;q23), which results in the juxtaposition of a strong transcriptional enhancer from the immunoglobulin heavy chain (IGH) gene locus with the promoter region of the MAF gene. This rearrangement is associated with multiple myeloma.
The science concerned with the normal processes of the stomach and intestines and how they are affected by drugs or disease.

A fusion gene that results from a chromosomal translocation, t(14;20)(q32;q12), which fuses transcriptional enhancers from the immunoglobulin heavy chain (IGH) gene locus with the promoter region of the MAFB gene. This rearrangement is associated with multiple myeloma, monoclonal gammopathy of undetermined significance (MGUS), smoldering myeloma, plasma cell leukemia and plasmacytoma.
A clonal lymphoproliferative disorder composed of neoplastic B-cells. It includes B-cell non-Hodgkin lymphomas, B-cell leukemias, and plasma cell myeloma.

A fusion gene that results from a chromosomal rearrangement involving the long arm of chromosome 14 (specifically 14q32). Most rearrangements involving 14q32 result in the juxtaposition of a strong transcriptional enhancer from the immunoglobulin heavy chain (IGH) gene locus with the promoter region for another gene; this promoter exchange process leads to overexpression or aberrant expression of the protein encoded by the fusion partner and is associated with various B-cell malignancies.
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to allelic gain within the chromosomal arm 1p.

An immunoglobulin G (IgG)-like bispecific T-cell engaging antibody directed against both natural cytotoxicity triggering receptor 3 ligand 1 (NCR3LG1; B7-H6) and T-cell surface antigen CD3, with potential immunostimulating and antineoplastic activities. Upon administration, anti-B7-H6/anti-CD3 bispecific antibody BI 765049 targets and binds to both B7-H6 on tumor cells and CD3 on T-cells. This results in the cross-linking of B7-H6-expressing tumor cells and T-cells, redirects cytotoxic T-lymphocytes (CTLs) to B7-H6-expressing tumor cells, which leads to the CTL-mediated cell death of B7-H6-expressing tumor cells. B7-H6, a member of the B7 family of immune modulators, is expressed in a variety of tumor cell types while minimally or not expressed in normal tissues. It is a specific ligand for the natural killer (NK) cell activating receptor NKp30, and may modulate NK cell function in certain cancers.
A 10-item, self-reported questionnaire for patients 18 years and older that uses a 5-point Likert scale to describe an individual's experience with fatigue.
A bone marrow aspiration that does not yield any bone marrow material.
Parathyroid gland hyperplasia that occurs in the absence of physiological stimuli.
Parathyroid gland hyperplasia that occurs in response to physiological stimuli (e.g., vitamin D deficiency, hyperphosphatemia, and hypocalcemia).

Parathyroid gland hyperplasia that results from progression of secondary hyperparathyroidism in which the parathyroid glands secrete parathyroid hormone autonomously, despite the presence of elevated parathyroid hormone and calcium levels in the serum.
Models of human disease produced through gene knockout methods

label.value: Mast Cell Leukemia with an Associated Myeloid Neoplasm

value.value: Mast cell leukemia associated with another clonal non-mast cell myeloid neoplasm (e.g., myelodysplastic syndrome, myeloproliferative neoplasm, and acute myeloid leukemia).
Bladder urothelial carcinoma that is amenable to surgical resection.
